Now I've traced the code paths quite carefully. Both JDBC and MongoDB DML paths should work with DbMapper through the `DbStatementBase.namedParam()` and `indexedParam()` methods. The mapper is invoked in those methods, which use `context().dbMapperManager()`.

Wait... Let me look at when `doExecute` is called in `JdbcTransactionStatementDml.execute()`:

```java
@Override
public long execute() {
    return doExecute((future, context) -> JdbcStatementDml.doExecute(this, future, context));
}
```

And `doExecute` in `DbStatementBase`:

```java
protected <T> T doExecute(BiFunction<CompletableFuture<Long>, DbClientServiceContext, T> function) {
    ...
    DbClientServiceContext serviceContext =
            new DbClientServiceContextImpl(context, statementType(), stmtFuture, queryFuture, parameters);
    ...
}
```

Here `parameters` is `this.parameters` - the `DbStatementParameters` field. If `namedParam()` was called, this field has been set with `DbNamedStatementParameters`.

But wait, look at `JdbcStatementDml.execute()`:
```java
@Override
public long execute() {
    return doExecute((future, context) -> {
        try {
            return doExecute(this, future, context);
        } finally {
            closeConnection();
        }
    });
}
```

It calls `doExecute` (static method in JdbcStatementDml). But note the naming conflict - `doExecute` is also the name of the instance method in `DbStatementBase`. The lambda parameter `context` becomes the `DbClientServiceContext` from `doExecute`.

And in `JdbcStatementDml.doExecute()`:
```java
static long doExecute(JdbcStatement<? extends DbStatementDml> dbStmt,
                      CompletableFuture<Long> future,
                      DbClientServiceContext context) {
    try (PreparedStatement statement = dbStmt.prepareStatement(context)) {
        ...
    }
}
```

This calls `dbStmt.prepareStatement(context)` which is `JdbcStatement.prepareStatement(DbClientServiceContext)`, which reads `serviceContext.statementParameters()`.

So the flow is:
1. User calls `.namedParam(pokemon)` → `DbStatementBase.namedParam()` → `context().dbMapperManager().toNamedParameters(...)` → returns Map → calls `params(Map)` → stores in `this.parameters`
2. User calls `.execute()` → `JdbcStatementDml.execute()` → `DbStatementBase.doExecute()` → creates `DbClientServiceContext` with `this.parameters`
3. `JdbcStatementDml.doExecute()` → `JdbcStatement.prepareStatement(context)` → reads parameters from `context.statementParameters()`

This looks correct!

